B3^Microworld level^^^^^^^^^^What happens when it is not the opponent's turn ?  Control passes
to a cluster of microworlds.  Each microworld responds to
a situation it can recognize. When a pattern is recognized, a slot in the perspective is
filled. When the associated perspective slots are filled, the functions of a
microworld are activated and they execute, proposing an action.  For example,
in a microworld which blocks an opponent's winning, the recognition of the threat
implicit in opponent's markers in cells 1 and 4  results in proposing a move to cell 7.  Such a proposed move is effected if it is uncontested.  What happens when more than one threat is recognized (as in a fork) or
when a threat-blocking proposal confronts a proposal to win the game by a 
different move ?  The answer to this question is a mixture of representation
choice and empirical observation.  I choose  to represent the structures which respond stepwise to developing
games as a set of three competing microworlds. One (WIN) recognizes ways to
to win.  A second (BLOCK) recognizes opponent's threats. The third (POSITION)
directs the next move when neither a win is immediately possible nor a threat
is recognized.  If three such microworlds compete with each other in responding
to a specific QUERY ( as I assume they do),  we can represent them, as in Figure 2, by a cluster of microworlds sharing input and output lines.

