with a fundamentally serial charcter to work at all.  Either we should reject this image of what rule insertion might mean or accept it and leave as a mystery why Miriam was able to only learn one of the three rules I proposed.  I believe, finally, we should reject this image because such a change would ignore the existence of the CORNERS world which became increasingly a nuclear entity in the developing structure of the strategic worlds.  We choose to represent the interaction of the Block and Corners worlds by Block's choking off the output of strategic play before the latter chokes the tactical cluster.  The choice can be seen as coherent with two other features of the structure already deemed valuable.  The Block world inhibits the output of the strategic worlds as did Miriam's knowledge of her brother's play.  The bias of choice between the output generally of the tacitcal and strategic worlds is preserved but is interrupted only when the Block world proposes a specific move.  This leaves us with an unimpeded flow of input through a hierarchically organized, clustered, competitive structure.

